        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/pickle_umbrella/{size}/48004_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-05-28T07:58:48.582Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"6vbz6d8ooppxhw1a\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"69293\" data-full=\"true\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/6/ce7236/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> 6vbz6d8ooppxhw1a:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Anyway, it would be really cool if I could completely eliminate the need for a phone line and just use a more private and fully encrypted form of communication, instead.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Phones have been around for over a century and are accessible by nearly everybody. Signal is a messaging app with around 70 million active users (according to <a href=\"https://www.businessofapps.com/data/signal-statistics/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">this site</a>). For that reason, no business would exclusively switch to Signal. Some businesses do use apps like Facebook, Instagram, Twitter/X, etc. for their business. However, the purpose of using these social media apps seems to be marketing, not messaging. Signal is not a social media, so I donâ€™t foresee businesses ever using Signal for that purpose. Overall, itâ€™s unlikely that businesses will use Signal for this purpose, it just doesnâ€™t make sense. Signal is relatively unpopular while the phone system is universal. If Signal became the most popular means of communication, surpassing Whatsapp, Facebook Messenger, and regular phone calls/sms messages, then many businesses would use it. That probably wonâ€™t ever happen though, which is fine. The purpose of Signal is to be an extremely secure and functional messenger, not a customer support or business management platform.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"6vbz6d8ooppxhw1a\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"69293\" data-full=\"true\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/6/ce7236/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> 6vbz6d8ooppxhw1a:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It would also be very useful to have a alias system which permits you to create a burner identity to use for each retailer, like DuckDuckGoâ€™s eMail relay system. You can generate a unique address per person you give it out to, and they all just get forwarded back to your main account. That way if you ever need to deny someone access, you can just delete that identity and they will loose the ability to send you any more messages. Although Iâ€™d prefer a system which doesnâ€™t inform them you deleted it, and just drops the messages (fowards them to null).</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>This seems like an entirely different feature request. I have heard of platforms with a similar feature like <a href=\"https://simplex.chat/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">SimpleX</a>. Iâ€™ve never used their platform, so Iâ€™m not 100% how they implemented this feature. This is a feature to enhance anonymity, which to my understanding is not a core goal of Signal. I donâ€™t think this would ever be implemented into Signal because of that. As an alternate you can use the username system and change it after giving it out to each person, along with changing your contact name.</p>",
